      'description' => 'The Basilique du Sacré-Cœur de Montmartre crowns the Butte Montmartre at 130 metres above sea level, its white Romano-Byzantine dome visible from virtually every corner of Paris on a clear day. Construction began in 1875, following the traumatic defeat of France in the Franco-Prussian War of 1870-71 and the bloody suppression of the Paris Commune — a radical workers\' government that had briefly seized control of the city. The basilica was conceived as an act of national penance and spiritual renewal, funded entirely by public subscription from Catholics across France who donated in their hundreds of thousands. The architect Paul Abadie — best known for his restoration of medieval churches — designed the building in a deliberately Romanesque-Byzantine style that evokes the Christian architecture of early medieval France and Constantinople, creating something that feels ancient yet was completed only in 1914. The exterior owes its distinctive brilliant white colour to the Château-Landon limestone from which it is built: this stone has the remarkable property of secreting calcite when it rains, meaning the building actually whitens with age rather than darkening. Step inside to see the vast Christ in Majesty mosaic above the altar — at 475 square metres, one of the largest mosaics in the world — and climb the dome for arguably the finest panoramic view in all of Paris: on exceptionally clear days, you can see up to 50 kilometres in every direction.',
