$tours[] = [
  'title' => 'Kafka\'s Prague: Jewish Quarter, Castle & the Art of Beer',
  'description' => 'Prague is one of Europe\'s most perfectly preserved medieval cities, saved from the bombing of the Second World War by the decision of American and British commanders to spare the Bohemian capital — a decision that has left Central Europe\'s finest collection of Romanesque, Gothic, Baroque, and Art Nouveau architecture intact and available for the astonishment of the 8 million visitors who arrive each year. This tour explores three of the city\'s defining dimensions: the Josefov — the historic Jewish Quarter, one of the best-preserved Jewish communities in Europe and home to six extraordinary synagogues — the soaring Gothic and Baroque complex of the Prague Castle (the largest castle complex in the world), and the city\'s extraordinary beer culture, which is not an afterthought but a genuine art form with a history stretching back to the 12th century. Threading through it all is the ghost of Franz Kafka, who was born in Josefov in 1883 and spent his entire life in Prague, writing in German about a world of absurd, impenetrable bureaucratic power — and seeing his city transform from a provincial Habsburg backwater into one of the most celebrated destinations in Europe.',
  'duration' => 210,
