    [
      'title' => 'Hungarian Parliament Building — Neo-Gothic on the Danube',
      'order' => 5,
      'location' => ['lat' => 47.5072, 'lng' => 19.0454],
      'description' => 'The Hungarian Parliament Building, Országház, on the Pest bank of the Danube is one of the great architectural spectacles of Europe and the most recognisable symbol of Budapest, its neo-Gothic silhouette of 96 towers, spires, and pinnacles reflected in the Danube creating an image that has graced a thousand postcards and yet never fails to astonish on first sight. Built between 1885 and 1904 to designs by Imre Steindl, the Parliament is the third-largest parliament building in the world at 268 metres long, 123 metres wide, and 96 metres tall, the height, like the year of completion, deliberately chosen to reference 896, the year of the Magyar conquest of the Carpathian Basin and the founding of the Hungarian state. The building contains 691 rooms, 29 staircases, 10 courtyards, and 40 kilometres of corridors, and is covered inside and out with an extraordinary programme of decorative arts: Hungarian historical paintings, tapestries, sculptures, and ornamental stonework of the highest quality. The central dome is 96 metres high, supported by 16 pillars around which stand statues of Hungarian rulers from Árpád, the leader of the Magyar conquest, to Ferdinand I. Beneath the dome, the Holy Crown of Hungary, one of the most symbolically potent objects in Central European history, the crown used to crown Hungarian kings since the 11th century and hidden by Hungarian diplomats in Fort Knox from 1945 until its return in 1978, is displayed under permanent guard in the Hall of the Crown. Guided tours of the interior are available daily, and tickets should be booked in advance, particularly in summer.',
