      'location' => ['lat' => 47.5012, 'lng' => 19.0631],
      'description' => 'Stretching northeast from the inner city to City Park, Andrássy Avenue is Budapest\'s grandest boulevard, a UNESCO World Heritage Site in its own right, and a street of multiple identities that embodies the turbulent history of the 20th century with unusual directness. Laid out between 1872 and 1885, the avenue was conceived as Budapest\'s answer to Paris\'s Champs-Élysées, a 2.3-kilometre promenade of neo-Renaissance palaces, French-influenced townhouses, luxury shops, and theatre buildings culminating in the grand neoclassical colonnades of Heroes\' Square and City Park beyond. The Hungarian State Opera House, opened in 1884 at number 22 and widely considered one of the most beautiful opera houses in the world, was designed by Miklós Ybl with a neo-Renaissance façade and an auditorium of breathtaking gilt-and-velvet opulence. Emperor Franz Joseph I attended the opening, reportedly insisting that Vienna\'s opera house, which Ybl had been inspired by, should be declared the finer of the two, a diplomatic necessity he enforced by reducing Budapest\'s state subsidy. Number 60 Andrássy Avenue is one of the most chilling addresses in the city and in Central European history: this handsome neo-Renaissance building served first as the headquarters of the fascist Arrow Cross party from 1944 to 1945, who used its basement as a torture and execution facility during the brief but catastrophic period of their rule; and then as the headquarters of the AVH, Hungary\'s communist secret police from 1945 to 1956, who continued using the same basement for the same purposes. Today it houses the House of Terror museum, a powerful and harrowing memorial to the victims of both totalitarian regimes, designed with artistic and architectural boldness that has made it one of the most discussed history museums in Europe.',
