  'steps' => [
    [
      'title' => 'The Duomo — Brunelleschi\'s Dome',
      'order' => 1,
      'location' => ['lat' => 43.7731, 'lng' => 11.2560],
      'description' => 'The Cattedrale di Santa Maria del Fiore, the Duomo, is Florence\'s most recognisable landmark and the building that more than any other embodies the ambition, ingenuity, and artistic confidence of the Renaissance. The cathedral was begun in 1296 to designs by Arnolfo di Cambio in the Italian Gothic style, and the nave, campanile, and baptistery were largely complete by the mid-14th century, yet one enormous problem remained. A 42-metre octagonal opening had been left at the crossing for the dome, but no one knew how to span it. The solution eluded engineers and architects for more than 50 years until Filippo Brunelleschi, a goldsmith turned architect with no formal masonry training, proposed an audacious plan in 1418: he would build not one dome but two, one inside the other, using herringbone brickwork and self-supporting rings that removed the need for the traditional wooden centring. Completed in 1436 after 16 years of construction, the dome is 45 metres in diameter at the base and 91 metres tall, making it the largest masonry dome in the world, a title it still holds six centuries later. Climbing the 463 steps between the two shells to the lantern reveals the engineering from the inside, with the herringbone pattern, the rising ribs, and, at the top, a vertiginous view of Florence that Brunelleschi himself never saw from this angle. The adjacent Baptistery of San Giovanni, with Lorenzo Ghiberti\'s celebrated bronze Gates of Paradise, now in the Museo dell\'Opera del Duomo, is one of Florence\'s oldest buildings and was already revered as the city\'s most ancient monument in Dante\'s time.',
