    [
      'title' => 'Galleria dell\'Accademia — Michelangelo\'s David',
      'order' => 4,
      'location' => ['lat' => 43.7767, 'lng' => 11.2588],
      'description' => 'A ten-minute walk north of the Duomo, the Galleria dell\'Accademia houses one of the most famous sculptures in the world and a work whose physical presence, even after centuries of reproduction, continues to stun visitors into silence: Michelangelo\'s David, carved between 1501 and 1504 from a single block of Carrara marble that had been quarried 40 years earlier and abandoned as impossible to work, damaged and with an awkward shape, far too narrow for the standing figure it was meant to produce. Michelangelo, then 26 years old, accepted the commission and within three years had produced the most celebrated male nude in Western art, a figure 5.17 metres tall whose anatomical precision, psychological intensity, and sheer physical beauty have never been surpassed in marble. The subject is the Biblical hero David, but Michelangelo\'s interpretation is entirely original: rather than showing the victorious moment after the battle as Donatello and Verrocchio had done before him, he shows David before the encounter with Goliath, in the instant of decision, his body tense with barely contained energy and his expression combining absolute concentration with a trace of awareness that what he is about to do may be beyond even his formidable capability. The veins on the back of his right hand, the torsion of the neck, the oversized hands and head, deliberately exaggerated to correct for the viewing angle from below, every detail rewards sustained study. The hall in which the David stands was specifically designed by Giuseppe Martini in 1882 with a skylit barrel-vaulted tribune to display it, visible from the entrance 60 metres away, making the walk toward it one of the most dramatically conceived museum experiences in the world.',
      'translations' => [
        'es' => [
          'title' => 'Galería de la Academia — el David de Miguel Ángel',
          'description' => 'A diez minutos a pie al norte del Duomo, la Galleria dell\'Accademia alberga una de las esculturas más famosas del mundo: el David de Miguel Ángel, tallado entre 1501 y 1504 en un único bloque de mármol de Carrara que había sido extraído 40 años antes y abandonado por imposible de trabajar. Miguel Ángel, con solo 26 años, aceptó el encargo y en tres años creó el desnudo masculino más célebre del arte occidental, una figura de 5,17 metros de altura cuya precisión anatómica, intensidad psicológica y belleza física nunca han sido superadas en mármol. En lugar de mostrar el momento victorioso después de la batalla, representa a David antes del encuentro con Goliat, en el instante de la decisión. La sala donde se expone fue diseñada específicamente para la obra, con una tribuna iluminada desde arriba que convierte la llegada en una de las experiencias más impactantes de Florencia.',
