      'description' => 'Cross the Arno River via the famous Ponte Vecchio, the Old Bridge, the only bridge in Florence not destroyed by the retreating Germans in 1944, spared apparently on the personal orders of Hitler, who wanted to preserve the view, and enter the Oltrarno, the neighbourhood beyond the Arno that is in many respects the most authentically Florentine part of the city. The Oltrarno has always had a slightly independent, artisan character: its streets are full of traditional craft workshops, leather workers, restorers, gilders, frame makers, and bookbinders operating in studios that have sometimes been in the same family for generations. The Palazzo Pitti, the enormous Renaissance palace that dominates the southern bank, was originally built in 1458 for the merchant Luca Pitti as a deliberately larger version of the Medici palace, an act of competitive ostentation that backfired when Pitti went bankrupt and the Medici bought the palace they had inadvertently inspired. Duke Cosimo I moved the Medici court here in 1550, and it remained the principal residence of the Florentine and later Italian rulers until 1919. Today the palace complex contains five separate museums: the Palatine Gallery holds the Medici\'s private art collection, with Raphael, Titian, Rubens, and Caravaggio in extraordinary concentration in rooms still decorated as they were when the paintings were hung; the Royal Apartments show the 19th-century state rooms; and the Boboli Gardens behind, a 45,000 square metre terraced Renaissance garden of fountains, grottoes, statues, and cypress alleys climbing the hill above the palace, offer the finest view of Florence from the south.',
