      'location' => ['lat' => 43.7754, 'lng' => 11.2537],
      'description' => 'Complete your Florentine experience in the neighbourhood of San Lorenzo, the Medici\'s own parish church and the commercial heart of the city, centred on the extraordinary Mercato Centrale, Florence\'s covered food market, housed in a spectacular two-storey cast-iron and glass structure built in 1874 by the engineer Giuseppe Mengoni. The ground floor is a working wholesale and retail food market of the finest Tuscan produce: whole prosciutti hanging in rows, wheels of Parmigiano, fresh pasta in every conceivable shape, Chianina beef, truffles, aged balsamic, local wines, and the extraordinary variety of Florentine street food, in particular the lampredotto sandwich, tripe slow-cooked in broth and served in a bun dipped in the cooking liquid with a spoonful of green sauce, the quintessential Florentine working-class lunch, eaten at market stalls since the medieval period. The Basilica di San Lorenzo beside the market was the Medici family parish church, rebuilt by Brunelleschi from 1419 in the purest early Renaissance style, a masterwork of classical proportion and harmonious geometry that influenced Italian church architecture for the next two centuries. The Old Sacristy, designed by Brunelleschi, and the New Sacristy, designed by Michelangelo, who carved the extraordinary tomb sculptures of Lorenzo and Giuliano de Medici, attached to the basilica contain some of the most significant Renaissance sculpture outside the Accademia. The adjacent Biblioteca Medicea Laurenziana, also by Michelangelo, is the greatest repository of humanist manuscripts in the world and one of the most innovative pieces of architecture the Renaissance produced.',
