      'location' => ['lat' => 45.4851, 'lng' => 12.4175],
      'description' => 'Take the 40-minute vaporetto ride from the Fondamente Nove to the island of Burano, one of the most visually arresting places in the entire Venetian Lagoon and a place of startling, joyful beauty that offers complete relief from the crowds and grandeur of the main islands. Burano is a fishing village of approximately 2,500 inhabitants clustered along four narrow canals and famous throughout the world for two things: its tradition of handmade needle lace, which was the most valuable textile in 16th and 17th-century Europe, a single elaborate collar could cost the equivalent of a palace, and its painted houses, which are the most intensely and variously coloured buildings in Italy. Every house is a different shade of red, orange, pink, yellow, blue, green, and purple, the colours regulated by a local government system that assigns each family their permitted palette. The legend behind the colours is romantic if possibly apocryphal: fishermen painted their houses in bright contrasting colours so they could recognise them from the lagoon through the mist. The Scuola dei Merletti (Lace Museum) tells the history of Buranella lace with remarkable detail, including the story of how the industry died in the 18th century when Venetian trade declined and was revived in the late 19th century by a school established to support the island\'s impoverished widows. Genuine handmade Burano lace, distinguished from cheaper machine-made or imported imitations by its irregular texture and the presence of the artisan\'s card, is among the finest textile crafts in Europe. Pieces can take months to produce and prices reflect this. The main canal and the campi behind it are lined with restaurants serving fresh lagoon seafood: crab, scallops, soft-shell crab, the seasonal moleche, and grilled fish of remarkable freshness and quality.',
