$tours[] = [
  'title' => 'Dubrovnik: The Pearl of the Adriatic — Walls, Sea & the Republic of Ragusa',
  'description' => 'George Bernard Shaw famously wrote: "Those who seek paradise on Earth should come to Dubrovnik." It is one of the most quoted sentences in travel writing, and while hyperbole is the language of tourism, in this case the exaggeration is barely perceptible. Dubrovnik is one of the best-preserved medieval walled cities on earth, a compact marvel of Gothic, Renaissance, and Baroque architecture perched on a limestone promontory above the impossibly blue Adriatic Sea on the southern coast of Croatia, and its UNESCO-listed old town — entered through fortress gates, pedestrianised entirely, and enclosed within walls that took centuries to build and centuries of determined citizens to maintain — is a place of extraordinary beauty that has earned its reputation as Europe\'s finest city. For five centuries from the 14th to the early 19th century, Dubrovnik was the capital of the independent Republic of Ragusa — a small but fiercely independent city-state that used diplomacy, commercial cunning, and a comprehensive system of international trade agreements to remain free when surrounded by larger and more powerful states. The Republic was one of the first in the world to abolish the slave trade (1416), to establish a quarantine system (1377 — the world\'s first, invented here to control the Black Death), and to create a public health service (1431). Its decline began with the catastrophic earthquake of 1667, which killed a quarter of the population and destroyed much of the medieval fabric — the Baroque buildings that replaced the Gothic originals are what visitors see today.',
