      'description' => 'Take the short ferry (15 minutes) from the old harbour to Lokrum — the small island 600 metres offshore that has been the wildest, most romantic, and most cursed spot in the Dubrovnik area for the better part of a thousand years. The island has been continuously associated with remarkable stories: Richard the Lionheart reportedly washed ashore here after a shipwreck in 1192 and, grateful for his survival, offered to fund the construction of a church on the island — the Ragusans diplomatically accepted his gratitude but redirected the funds to the Dubrovnik Cathedral, arguing it would be of more benefit to the city. A Benedictine monastery was established in the 11th century, suppressed by Napoleon\'s forces in 1798, and its monks supposedly placed a curse on anyone who attempted to take private ownership of the island — a curse that has been fulfilled with remarkable consistency: subsequent private owners include Archduke Maximilian of Austria (later Emperor Maximilian I of Mexico, executed in 1867), who built the formal gardens and cloisters still visible today; and the Duchess of Leuchtenberg, who sold it to the city after several inexplicable deaths. Today the island is a nature reserve of extraordinary beauty: endemic peacocks wander the paths freely, subtropical vegetation creates a lush green canopy, a saltwater lake in the centre (the Dead Sea) is warm enough for swimming in summer, and the rocky sea coast offers some of the clearest swimming water in the entire Adriatic. The Game of Thrones Iron Throne replica installed in the monastery cloister is the most visited artefact in Croatia.',
