  'title' => 'Royal Krakow: Dragons, Jewish Heritage & the Weight of History',
  'description' => 'Krakow is Poland\'s most beautiful city and the one that most completely preserves the layered identity of a Central European metropolis that has passed through medieval splendour, imperial grandeur, Nazi occupation, and communist suppression to emerge as one of the most visited and most culturally vibrant cities on the continent. Unlike Warsaw — which was systematically destroyed by the Nazis in 1944 and rebuilt from scratch after the war — Krakow was spared deliberate destruction, its architectural heritage preserved through a combination of historical circumstance and the efforts of its citizens. The result is a city whose medieval market square, Gothic cathedral, Renaissance castle, and historic Jewish quarter form a coherent urban landscape of extraordinary beauty that feels genuinely lived-in rather than museified. Krakow was Poland\'s royal capital from the 11th to the late 16th century, the coronation site of Polish kings, and the home of the Jagiellonian University — the second oldest university in Central Europe, founded in 1364, where Nicolaus Copernicus studied astronomy in the 1490s. The city\'s Jewish Quarter of Kazimierz, devastated in the Holocaust and later used as a film set for Schindler\'s List (Steven Spielberg filmed here in 1992), has since transformed into one of the most creative and culturally interesting neighbourhoods in Poland. Any visit to Krakow must also reckon with its proximity to Auschwitz-Birkenau — the largest Nazi extermination camp, where approximately 1.1 million people were murdered between 1940 and 1945 — 60 kilometres to the west. A visit there is not a tourist experience but a moral obligation.',
