      'location' => ['lat' => 50.0466, 'lng' => 19.9577],
      'description' => 'Cross the Vistula River to Podgórze — the district where the Nazis established the Krakow Ghetto in 1941, confining the remaining Jewish population behind walls into an area originally built for a quarter of the number of people now forced to inhabit it — to visit the Oskar Schindler Factory Museum, housed in the original enamelware factory on Lipowa Street where the German industrialist and improbable rescuer employed and thereby saved approximately 1,200 Jewish workers from deportation and death. The story of Schindler — an ethnic German from Czechoslovakia, a member of the Nazi party, initially a war profiteer who saw the occupation as an opportunity for cheap labour and personal enrichment — and his transformation into a genuine rescuer motivated by growing moral awareness of what the Nazi programme actually meant is one of the most complex and remarkable individual stories of the Second World War. Thomas Keneally\'s 1982 novel and Spielberg\'s film, with its devastating final scenes of survivors visiting Schindler\'s grave in Jerusalem, brought the story to global attention; the museum, opened in 2010, places it within the full historical context of the occupation of Krakow and the systematic murder of its Jewish population. The museum\'s permanent exhibition — "Krakow Under Nazi Occupation 1939-1945" — is one of the finest and most thoughtful historical museums in Poland, using the original factory spaces and an innovative combination of objects, documents, photographs, and personal testimonies to convey both the administrative machinery of mass murder and the human reality of individual experience within it. The museum is deliberately demanding: allow two hours and expect to be profoundly affected.',
