  'title' => 'Athens: The Acropolis, Democracy & the Western Mind',
  'description' => 'Athens is where the West began. In this compact, sun-bleached city at the southern tip of the Balkan Peninsula, surrounded by mountains and facing the Aegean Sea, a small community of around 30,000 free male citizens in the 5th century BC invented democracy, tragedy, philosophy, history, and architectural forms that still define how Western civilisation conceives of government, art, and reason. The Parthenon on the Acropolis, built between 447 and 432 BC as an act of democratic cultural assertion, remains 2,500 years after its completion the most influential building ever constructed: its proportions, formal language, and civic symbolism have been replicated in the parliaments, banks, museums, and public buildings of every Western democracy from Washington DC to Canberra. Modern Athens is a chaotic, passionate, frequently maddening, and ultimately utterly fascinating city of 3.7 million people, sun-drenched and loud, its ancient marbles rising improbably above the concrete sprawl of the 20th century. The archaeological sites are extraordinary, the food is excellent, and the light, the famous Attic light that Plato described as the medium of truth, is unlike anything else in Europe.',
