      'description' => 'The Acropolis, literally "the high city", is the defining monument of Western civilisation and one of the most visited and most significant archaeological sites in the world. A flat-topped limestone outcrop rising 156 metres above Athens, it was fortified and inhabited from the Neolithic period, served as the residence of the Mycenaean kings, and was transformed in the 5th century BC under Pericles and the sculptor Pheidias into the greatest concentration of architectural and sculptural achievement in the ancient world. The Parthenon, dedicated to Athena Parthenos, was built entirely in Pentelic marble and combined refined proportion with an ambitious sculptural programme that included metopes, a continuous frieze, and monumental pediments. It later served as a temple, a church, and a mosque, was severely damaged in 1687, and has been under restoration since 1975. Nearby, the Propylaea offers a brilliant example of how sacred boundaries and architectural design could be turned into a dramatic ceremonial entrance.',
