    [
      'title' => 'The Acropolis Museum — Marble in Context',
      'order' => 2,
      'location' => ['lat' => 37.9688, 'lng' => 23.7293],
      'description' => 'At the foot of the Acropolis hill, the Acropolis Museum opened in 2009 in a spectacular building designed by Bernard Tschumi to display the surviving sculptures from the Acropolis monuments in the context of the city they came from. The glass, concrete, and steel structure is built over an active archaeological excavation, and its top floor is rotated 23 degrees to align precisely with the Parthenon visible above through the panoramic windows. The museum houses the most significant surviving fragments of the Parthenon sculptural decoration, as well as the Erechtheion caryatids, displayed at eye level so their individuality can be appreciated properly. The top gallery mirrors the orientation of the temple above, making the case for the return of the Elgin Marbles more powerfully than any argument alone could.',
