      'description' => 'The National Archaeological Museum of Athens is the largest and most important museum of ancient Greek art and culture in the world, housing a collection that spans 7,000 years of human history from the Neolithic period to late antiquity. Housed in a vast neoclassical building begun in 1866, its galleries contain more than 8,000 exhibits, and the highlights are extraordinary. The Mycenaean Gold Collection includes the treasures excavated by Heinrich Schliemann from the shaft graves of Mycenae, including the famous gold funerary mask long associated with Agamemnon. The Antikythera Mechanism, recovered from a shipwreck in 1901, is a bronze mechanical device designed to predict astronomical events, eclipse cycles, and the dates of the Olympic Games. Its surviving gearwork reveals a level of ancient technical sophistication that changed modern understanding of Greek science and engineering.',
