      'description' => 'Take the coastal road or hire a car for the drive south from Athens to Cape Sounion, where the Temple of Poseidon stands on a cliff above the Aegean Sea and offers one of the most magnificent sunset views in the Mediterranean. The cape has been sacred to Poseidon since at least the Bronze Age, and the current temple was built in the 5th century BC in the Doric order using Agrileza marble. Its surviving columns were visible to sailors approaching Attica for centuries, making the sanctuary both a religious site and a coastal landmark. The headland is also associated with the story of Aegeus and Theseus: when Theseus returned from Crete after killing the Minotaur, his father Aegeus saw the ship\'s black sails and threw himself from the cliff in grief, giving the Aegean Sea its name. Lord Byron is also linked to Sounion, and his name was reportedly carved into one of the temple columns during his visit in 1810.',
      'translations' => [
        'es' => [
          'title' => 'Cabo Sunión y el Templo de Poseidón',
