$tours[] = [
  'title' => 'Berlin: Wall, Memory and the Reinvention of a Capital',
  'description' => 'Berlin is the most historically charged city in Europe and, arguably, the most important. No other city on earth has been so completely at the centre of the defining catastrophes of the 20th century: the First World War ended here in a revolution that toppled the Kaiser and created the doomed Weimar Republic, the rise of Nazism and the implementation of the Holocaust were administered from here, the Second World War was fought to its end on these streets, and for 28 years, from 1961 to 1989, the city was literally divided by a wall that served as the most visible symbol of the Cold War and the most concrete expression of what totalitarianism means for individual human lives. Since reunification in 1990, Berlin has reinvented itself with remarkable energy and creativity as Germany\'s capital, its cultural capital, and one of the most vital cities in Europe for art, music, architecture, and intellectual life. The city bears its history not as a burden but as a responsibility: the Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe, the Topography of Terror, the East Side Gallery, and dozens of memorials, museums, and Stolpersteine, brass plates set into the pavement marking the homes of Holocaust victims, make Berlin\'s engagement with its past the most serious and sustained programme of historical reckoning in the world.',
  'duration' => 210,
  'country' => 'Germany',
