$tours[] = [
  'title' => 'Munich: Royal Bavaria, Beer Halls and the Alps at the Edge of the City',
  'description' => 'Munich, known in German as München, is the most liveable large city in Germany and one of the most prosperous and culturally ambitious in Europe: the capital of Bavaria, a kingdom that maintained a fierce independence from the rest of Germany until 1871 and whose royal house, the Wittelsbachs, who ruled for 738 unbroken years from 1180 to 1918, channelled their wealth and genuine artistic sensibility into building a city of remarkable Baroque and Neoclassical grandeur. The city is best known internationally for Oktoberfest, the annual beer festival held on the Theresienwiese meadows that has grown from a royal wedding celebration in 1810 to the largest annual public festival in the world, attracting 6 to 7 million visitors over 16 to 18 days. But Munich\'s cultural ambitions go far beyond beer: the three Pinakothek museums form the finest art collection in Germany, the Deutsches Museum is the largest science and technology museum in the world, and the English Garden, larger than Central Park, is the finest urban park in Europe. The Alps begin a one-hour drive south of the city centre, and the combination of urban sophistication, royal heritage, beer culture, and immediate access to mountain landscape gives Munich an appeal that its residents exploit with unselfconscious enthusiasm.',
  'duration' => 195,
