  'title' => 'Seville: Flamenco, Mudéjar Splendour and the Gateway to the New World',
  'description' => 'Seville is the most sensually magnificent city in Spain and the capital of Andalusia, a city of extraordinary architectural beauty, passionate music, and a historical identity formed at the intersection of three cultures: the Roman who called it Hispalis, the Moorish who named it Isbiliya and made it one of the great cities of medieval Europe, and the Christian who conquered it in 1248 and from whose ports Christopher Columbus departed for the Americas in 1492, making Seville for over a century the richest city in the Western world as the gateway of the Spanish empire. The extraordinary Alcázar palace complex, still a royal residence and the oldest continuously occupied palace in Europe, the enormous Gothic Cathedral with its Moorish bell tower and Columbus\'s tomb, and the ornate María Luisa Park with its 1929 World\'s Fair pavilions are all UNESCO World Heritage sites and represent the full sweep of Sevillian architectural ambition. But the true character of the city is felt most strongly in its barrios: in the Triana neighbourhood across the Guadalquivir where flamenco was born, in the Santa Cruz labyrinth of the former Jewish quarter, and in the tapas bars along the Alameda de Hércules where the evening begins at 10pm and ends sometime the following morning.',
  'duration' => 195,
