    [
      'title' => 'Seville Cathedral and La Giralda',
      'order' => 1,
      'location' => ['lat' => 37.3858, 'lng' => -5.9930],
      'description' => 'The Catedral de Santa María de la Sede, Seville Cathedral, is the largest Gothic cathedral in the world and, after St. Peter\'s in Rome and St. Paul\'s in London, the largest church building in the world by volume. It was built between 1401 and 1528 on the site of the former Great Mosque of Seville, the mosque built by the Almohad dynasty in the late 12th century and considered one of the finest in the Islamic world, incorporating the mosque\'s minaret and courtyard while demolishing the prayer hall. The scale of the undertaking is suggested by the minutes of the chapter meeting that authorised the project in 1401: "Let us build a church so large that those who see it finished will think we were mad." They were not wrong: the cathedral is 126 metres long, 83 metres wide, and 30 metres to the vaulted ceiling, its five naves creating an interior of overwhelming and somewhat vertiginous scale. The high altar retablo, the altarpiece completed in 1564, is the largest altarpiece in the world at 27 metres high and 18 metres wide, containing 45 carved scenes from the lives of Christ and the Virgin executed in gilded timber over four generations by successive master craftsmen. The tomb of Christopher Columbus, carried by four allegorical kings representing the kingdoms of Castile, León, Navarra, and Aragon, stands in the south transept. His remains were brought here from Havana in 1898 following the Spanish-American War, a final homecoming of sorts for the man whose voyage had set the entire Atlantic world in motion four centuries earlier. The Giralda, the former minaret of the mosque, stands 93 metres tall and is the unmistakable symbol of Seville: its Almohad brickwork, the Renaissance bell chamber added in 1568, and the bronze weathervane at the summit known as the Giraldillo, a female figure representing Faith, are visible across the rooftops of the city. It is climbed not by stairs but by 35 ramps originally designed wide enough to accommodate the imam\'s horse, which means the ascent is surprisingly easy and the views from the top genuinely breathtaking.',
