  'title' => 'Porto: Azulejos, Port Wine and the Soul of the Douro',
  'description' => 'Porto, known as Portu in Latin, the name from which Portugal itself derives, is the second city of Portugal and arguably its most characterful: a compact, steep, beautiful city of granite and azulejo-clad houses tumbling down to the mouth of the Douro River, where the wine that bears its name has been aged in the lodges of Vila Nova de Gaia on the opposite bank for three centuries and exported to the world. Porto is a city that wears its history and its poverty with equal unselfconsciousness: magnificent Baroque churches rise from streets of crumbling houses, Art Nouveau bookshops operate in buildings whose tiles are falling from the walls, and a Roman city, a medieval Jewish quarter, and the memory of the Portuguese maritime empire are all present simultaneously in the same urban fabric. The city has been transformed in the last decade by tourism and investment, having been named European Best Destination three times in five years, but retains a roughness and authenticity that more polished cities have lost. The food is extraordinary: francesinha, a sandwich of cured meats and fresh sausage drowned in a spiced beer-and-tomato sauce and topped with a fried egg; bacalhau, salt cod prepared in 365 variations according to Portuguese culinary mythology; and bifanas, pork steak sandwiches, are the iconic dishes. The wine, obviously, is non-negotiable.',
