  'title' => 'Stockholm: Vikings, Scandinavian Design and the Archipelago Capital',
  'description' => 'Stockholm is arguably the most beautiful capital city in northern Europe, a metropolitan centre built across 14 islands at the point where Lake Mälaren meets the Baltic Sea, its waters, bridges, and green spaces giving it an openness and clarity that larger Continental capitals lack. Founded in the 13th century as a trading post controlling the vital waterway between the Baltic and the Swedish interior, Stockholm became the capital of the Swedish Empire in the 17th century when Sweden was briefly one of the great powers of Europe, and the city was endowed with the royal palaces, churches, and aristocratic townhouses that still define its historical core. Sweden\'s particular contribution to world culture, the design philosophy that insists on beauty, functionality, and democratic access to good design simultaneously, is visible everywhere in the city, from the furniture and interiors of the 17th-century houses of Gamla Stan to the iconic products of IKEA, Volvo, and the extraordinary tradition of Swedish graphic design. The city\'s museums are exceptional: the Vasa Museum, housing a complete 17th-century warship raised from the harbour in 1961, is the most visited museum in Scandinavia, while the ABBA Museum and the Nobel Museum reflect the city\'s dual cultural personality of pop phenomenon and intellectual seriousness. Beyond the city, the Stockholm archipelago, 30,000 islands, islets, and rocks stretching 80 kilometres into the Baltic, is one of the great natural environments of northern Europe.',
