  'steps' => [
    [
      'title' => 'Torvehallerne, the New Nordic Market',
      'order' => 1,
      'location' => ['lat' => 55.6830, 'lng' => 12.5657],
      'description' => 'Copenhagen\'s food culture, which has produced more Michelin stars per capita than any other city in the world over the last fifteen years, with Noma and Geranium among the most globally influential restaurants of the 21st century, is accessible in concentrated form at Torvehallerne, the glass-and-steel covered market hall on Israels Plads that opened in 2011 and immediately became the food hub of the city. The market consists of two parallel glass halls and an outdoor market area housing approximately 60 vendors of produce, street food, and specialty ingredients, organised to serve both the city\'s professional food culture, with wholesale produce vendors supplying Copenhagen\'s top restaurants, and everyday shopping for quality food by a population that takes what it eats seriously. The produce is organised around the founding principles of the New Nordic Kitchen: locality, with most produce drawn from Denmark and the broader Nordic region; seasonality, with the market changing radically between the root vegetables and preserved fish of winter and the extraordinary summer abundance of berries, herbs, and fresh vegetables; and quality above all else. The coffee culture is exceptional, and Copenhagen is one of the finest coffee cities in Europe: the concentration of specialty roasters, including Coffee Collective and Ønsk, rivals any city on the continent, and the flat white here will almost certainly be better than anything available in the city you came from. The smørrebrød stands, serving open-faced sandwiches of dark rye bread piled with pickled herring, smoked salmon, roast beef with remoulade, liver pâté with bacon, or combinations of vegetables and herbs from the New Nordic tradition, are a mandatory stop. Smørrebrød is Denmark\'s greatest contribution to the civilisation of lunch, and ordering it correctly, which means following the traditional sequence of fish, then meat, then cheese, is one of the small rituals that Copenhageners take very seriously indeed. The outdoor market on Friday and Saturday mornings, spreading across Israels Plads with additional vendors of flowers, vegetables, cheese, and street food, draws half the city\'s food-conscious population and is the closest thing Copenhagen has to a weekly civic festival.',
      'translations' => [
