$tours[] = [
  'title' => 'Bruges: The Perfectly Preserved Medieval Capital of the North',
  'description' => 'Bruges, known in Dutch as Brugge, is the most completely preserved medieval city in northern Europe and arguably the most beautiful small city on the continent: a compact UNESCO World Heritage Centre of canals, Gothic churches, Flemish step-gabled merchant houses, and medieval market squares that has survived largely intact from its 13th and 14th-century heyday, when it was one of the wealthiest and most commercially important cities in the world. At its peak in the 13th century, Bruges was the principal trading hub of northwestern Europe, the point at which goods from the Baltic (fur, timber, amber, fish), the Mediterranean (spices, silk, Italian banking), and England (wool and cloth) all converged in a single city whose Flemish craftsmen and merchants mediated between them. The great Flemish Primitive painters, Jan van Eyck, Hans Memling, and Gerard David, worked here during the city\'s golden age, producing the most technically accomplished paintings of the 15th century. When the river silted up in the early 16th century and trade migrated to Antwerp, Bruges was effectively frozen in time: no industrial revolution, no great railway terminus, no 19th-century expansion, just a small provincial city sleeping inside its medieval fabric until the 20th century discovered that this anachronism was exactly what the age of tourism had been looking for. The city today receives over 8 million visitors per year in a population of 130,000, a ratio that creates real challenges for authentic daily life but has also sustained the preservation of its remarkable heritage.',
  'duration' => 165,
  'country' => 'Belgium',
  'city' => 'Bruges',
  'location' => ['lat' => 51.2093, 'lng' => 3.2247],
  'translations' => [
